You know how losing teams tend to remain losers and lose for decades at a time, some never actually being good?
It's because there wasn't a solid winning culture or infrastructure in place to stop them from losing. Every system they've done ended horridly, and they never get a winning culture established. In scouting, coaching, etc. This trickles down from every level to even the backups.

Meanwhile, teams with a winning culture in football tend to stay winning, rebound from rebuilding quicker, and have a system in place to keep winning.

49ers stay competitive even if they haven't won since the 90s, because they had a successful system in the 80s/90s, built on that foundation, and kept up the culture. Of course previously successful places also draw more talent because talent wants to go to places with a winning culture anyways.

Cowboys, 49ers, Steelers, Packers, Giants have all stayed competitive, and come back to playoffs regularly even after rebuilding years. They all have the most rings. Patriots, staying competitive, even if they're the newest example, I doubt the Patriots ever become the joke they were before again.

Only really a few times do successful NFL franchises become jokes, and normally the time they became jokes can be recorded in ownership change. Causing the rest of the failure to trickle down from ownership.

>>128721752
i thought you had that guy on a DM(d) role?
and with that guy staying put in front of your defence, it means your left back can go forwards to help with the attack
if your issue is conceding, then its probably wise to have your central midfielders on the same line at least as LCM and RCM
if samson is more mobile, have him as a BWM, and thompson as a DLP/CM(s/d)
and if thompson is more mobile keep him as BBM and just have samson as CM(d) - it doesnt matter if the stars go down, you need one of them to sit, BWM(d) chases the ball and keep the structure
id also remove dribble less OR be more expressive, maybe both, your players still arent massively smart at this level so more instructions will make it harder for them
dont be discouraged, only the teams that are significantly better than the rest of the league can expect to hit the ground running at the start of each season
unless you want your team to keep the ball for minutes at a time, then counter in transition will probably help too

One is a great finisher with an also remarkable air game. Period.
The other is arguably the best player in history at scoring, dribbling, short passing, long passing, creativity, vision, both individual and associated game, and mostly any other category by which you can judge a player that's not a defender or a GK.

Messi makes poeple stand up from their seats when he receives the ball, in expectation of what he might do.
Cristiano makes people stand up from their seats only after he scored, which we can even guess with almost no margin of error that it'll be a tap-in, a penalty, a header or, much more rarely, a shot from outside the box.

The Audi RS3 LMS TCR had a weird thing. It’s MQB whcih is also imo a great platform considering it’s a ‘budget’ platform, lots of aluminum available. But anyway the racecar was available in DSG double clutch from the road car and a dog box clutch straight cut traditional racing box whcih was lighter.

The DSG car owners woild complain about the weight and eventually got a bop adjustment to offset the weight of their box and something to do with acceleration of the first gear. Doesn’t matter. MQB has less options for weight loss so the teams woudl literally just cut holes in the floor in the back to try to get the weight down to the new bop minimum weight.

As far as I know the Bentley and M6/8 had no trouble at all reaching minimum weight for the rules.
